Entry and borders
See Entry requirements to find out what you will need to do when you arrive in Serbia.
Public spaces and services
Throughout Serbia protective face masks must be worn on public transport, there is a ban on gatherings of more than 200 people and the wearing of protective face masks is recommended in indoor public spaces.
Additional restrictions are in place in Belgrade, Novi Pazar, Kragujevac, Tutin, and Vranje where COVID19-related emergency situations have been declared and it is mandatory to wear protective face masks, without exception, in all indoor public spaces. In all these areas bar Belgrade, gatherings are limited to a maximum of 5 people, all swimming pools and spas are closed, as are bars and restaurants from 8pm-7am and nightclubs after 11pm.
In Belgrade, the same restrictions on pools, bars and restaurants and nightclubs apply, but gatherings are limited to 100 people indoors and 500 outdoors. Social distancing at all times is encouraged.
Schools and universities throughout Serbia are closed until further notice. Some kindergartens and day care facilities are open.
There may be further restrictions to limit the spread of coronavirus. Infringements of these procedures may result in fines and/or a prison sentence. If you are currently in Serbia, check news outlets regularly for up to date information.
